410→                           For $n=3$ the equilateral triangle is the only such set. For $n=4$ the square or two equilateral triangles sharing an edge give two non-similar examples.<br><br>For $n=5$ the regular pentagon is the unique such set (which has two distinct distances). Erdős mysteriously remarks in <a href="#cite-Er90-91" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er90','91'); return false;">[Er90]</a> this was proved by 'a colleague'. (In <a href="#cite-Er87b-91" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er87b','91'); return false;">[Er87b]</a> this is described as 'a colleague from Zagreb (unfortunately I do not have his letter)'.) A published proof of this fact is provided by Kovács <a href="#cite-Ko24c-91" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Ko24c','91'); return false;">[Ko24c]</a>.<br><br>In <a href="#cite-Er87b-91" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er87b','91'); return false;">[Er87b]</a> Erdős says that there are at least two non-similar examples for $6\leq n\leq 9$.<br><br>The minimal possible number of distinct distances is the subject of <a href="/89" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[89]</a>.
